body:
> Forgetting a configuration option (in this case --enable-mainnet) would lead to a not-in-production useful software. This is uncommon behaviour.

Just a thought, but one solution is we force users to explicitly choose `-mainnet` when starting `bitcoind` if they did not use the `--enable_mainnet` config.  We can add `-mainnet` as an option [here](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/595a7bab23bc21049526229054ea1fff1a29c0bf/src/chainparamsbase.cpp#L90) and then also check if not present in `init.cpp`:

```
  if (chain == CBaseChainParams::MAIN && !gArgs.GetBoolArg("-mainnet", false))
    return InitError("You did not configure with --enable-mainnet. You must set -testnet, -regtest or -mainnet option.");
```

@jtimon Thanks, will look through your commit.  Was going to simply add the new `fMainNet` boolean and the corresponding `if` block to check (see snippet below).  If none are set, will fall through and `init.cpp` will pick it up and throw the `InitError()`.

```
std::string ChainNameFromCommandLine()
{
    bool fRegTest = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-regtest", false);
    bool fTestNet = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-testnet", false);
    bool fMainNet = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-mainnet", false);

    if (fTestNet && fRegTest)
        throw std::runtime_error("Invalid combination of -regtest and -testnet.");
    if (fRegTest)
        return CBaseChainParams::REGTEST;
    if (fTestNet)
        return CBaseChainParams::TESTNET;
    if (fMainNet)
        return CBaseChainParams::MAINNET;
    return CBaseChainParams::MAIN;
}
```

I was thinking more on something like this:

```
std::string ChainNameFromCommandLine()
{
    bool fRegTest = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-regtest", false);
    bool fTestNet = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-testnet", false);
    bool fMainNet = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-mainnet", false);

    if (fTestNet + fRegTest + fMainNet > 1)
        throw std::runtime_error("Invalid combination of -mainnet, -regtest and -testnet.");
    if (fRegTest)
        return CBaseChainParams::REGTEST;
    if (fTestNet)
        return CBaseChainParams::TESTNET;
#ifndef ENABLE_MAINNET
    if (!fMainNet)
        throw std::runtime_error("You did not configure with --enable-mainnet. You must set -mainnet, -testnet or -regtest option.");
#endif
    return CBaseChainParams::MAIN;
}
```

This way you don't need to touch init at all, the init for this is already handled in src/qt/bitcoin.cpp, src/bitcoind.cpp, src/bitcoin-tx.cpp and src/bitcoin-cli.cpp, so no need to touch src/init.cpp if you do it here in ChainNameFromCommandLine(). Besides I think this way it stays better encapsulated.

Or alternatively (my preference), something like:

```
std::string ChainNameFromCommandLine()
{
    bool fRegTest = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-regtest", false);
    bool fTestNet = gArgs.GetBoolArg("-testnet", false);
    bool is_chain_arg_set = gArgs.IsArgSet("-chain");

    if (is_chain_arg_set + fRegTest + fTestNet > 1) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Invalid combination of -regtest, -testnet and -chain. Can use at most one.");
    }
    if (fRegTest)
        return CBaseChainParams::REGTEST;
    if (fTestNet)
        return CBaseChainParams::TESTNET;

#ifndef ENABLE_MAINNET
    if (!is_chain_arg_set) {
        throw std::runtime_error("You did not configure with --enable-mainnet. You must set -chain, -testnet or -regtest option.");
    }
#endif
    return gArgs.GetArg("-chain", CBaseChainParams::MAIN);
}
```

